hroughs that made modernist churches feasible themselves raised questions that were, for many Catholics, fundamentally theological. Couldn't technological improvements engender worship spaces that better reflected God's presence in the contemporary world? Detailing the social, architectural, and theological movements that made modern churches possible, American Catholics and the Churches of Tomorrow breaks important new ground in the history of American Catholicism, and also presents new lines of thought for scholars attracted to modern architectural and urban history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 22. Okt 2019) 0aCatholic church buildingszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aModern movement (Architecture)zUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aModernism (Christian theology)xCatholic ChurchxHistoryy20thcentury. 4aAmerican Catholicism. 4aCatholic Church. 4aChurch Architecture. 4aEcclesiology. 4aEschatology. 4aLiturgical Studies. 4aModern Architecture. 4aReligion and Science. 4aSecond Vatican Council. 4aVatican II. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018z978311063537940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226561165423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226561165.jpg  a978-3-11-063537-9  University of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles